n the league match against Motherwell on 10 April was his 229th competitive match for the club - overtaking [[John Miller (footballer, born 1890)|John Miller]]'s record set in the 1919-1920 season. And second, the league match against Third Lanark on 28 April would be Donegan's final game for the club - during his eight seasons with the club he set a new record of 230 appearances in all national competitive matches.</ref>|pos=FW|nat=SCO|23|4|0|0|6|2}}\n{{Efs player|name=Willie Gibson<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sonsarchive.com/player.php?id=213 |title=Willie Gibson - Player Statistics |publisher=The Sons Archive |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>|pos=FW|nat=SCO|7|3|1|0|0|0}}\n{{Efs player|name=[[Hugh Goldie (footballer, born 1923)|Hugh Goldie]]<ref>The league match against Motherwell on 7 November marked Hugh Goldie's 100th appearance for Dumbarton in all national competitions.</ref>|pos=FW|nat=SCO|17|4|0|0|6|2}}\n{{Efs player|name=[[Tony Hepburn]]|pos=FW|nat=SCO|15|6|1|0|5|0}}\n{{Efs player|name=[[Jim Maguire (footballer, born 1932)|Jim Maguire]]|pos=FW|nat=SCO|3|2|0|0|0|0}}\n{{Efs player|name=Jackie Malloch<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sonsarchive.com/player.php?id=200 |title=Jackie Malloch - Player Statistics |publisher=The Sons Archive |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>|pos=FW|nat=SCO|23|13|1|0|2|1}}\n{{Efs player|name=Tommy Martin<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sonsarchive.com/player.php?id=216 |title=Tommy Martin - Player Statistics |publisher=The Sons Archive |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>|pos=FW|nat=SCO|4|0|0|0|0|0}}\n{{Efs player|name=Gerry McCaffrey<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sonsarchive.com/player.php?id=124 |title=Gerry McCaffrey - Player Statistics |publisher=The Sons Archive |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>|pos=FW|nat=SCO|10|1|0|0|6|0}}\n{{Efs player|name=[[Tom McGairy]]|pos=FW|nat=SCO|16|7|1|0|1|0}}\n{{Efs player|name=[[Jock Weir]]|pos=FW|nat=SCO|16|5|1|0|0|0}}\n|}\n\n<small>Source:<ref>{{cite book |last=McAllister |first=Jim |title=The Sons of the Rock - The Official History of Dumbarton Football Club |publisher=J&J Robertson Printers |year=2002 |location=Dumbarton}}</ref></small>\n\n===Transfers===\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n==== Players in ====\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; font-size:95%;width:98%; text-align:left\"\n|-\n!Player\n!From\n!Date\n|-\n| {{flagicon|SCO}} [[Hugh Goldie (footballer, born 1923)|Hugh Goldie]]\n| {{flagicon|SCO}} [[Albion Rovers F.C.|Albion Rovers]] \n| 8 Aug 1953\n|-\n| {{flagicon|SCO}} [[Tom McGairy]]\n| {{flagicon|SCO}} [[Alloa Athletic F.C.|Alloa Athletic]] \n| 5 Sep 1953\n|-\n| {{flagicon|SCO}} Tommy Martin\n| {{flagicon|SCO}} [[Dundee F.C.|Dundee]] \n| 19 Sep 1953\n|-\n| {{flagicon|SCO}} [[John Black (footballer, born 1914)|John Black]]\n| {{flagicon|SCO}} [[Greenock Morton F.C.|Morton]] \n| 3 Oct 1953\n|-\n| {{flagicon|SCO}} Dick Cumming\n| {{flagicon|SCO}} [[Motherwell F.C.|Motherwell]] \n| 15 Oct 1953\n|-\n| {{flagicon|SCO}} [[Don Cornock]]\n| {{flagicon|SCO}} [[Clyde F.C.|Clyde]] \n| 7 Nov 1953\n|-\n| {{flagicon|SCO}} [[Ray Brown (footballer)|Ray Brown]]\n| {{flagicon|SCO}} [[Third Lanark F.C.|Third Lanark]]\n| 21 Nov 1953\n|-\n| {{flagicon|SCO}} [[Jock Weir]]\n| {{flagicon|WAL}} [[Llanelli Town A.F.C.|Llanelli]]\n| 16 Dec 1953\n|-\n| {{flagicon|SCO}} [[Walter Scott (footballer, born 1932)|Walter Scott]]\n| {{flagicon|SCO}} [[Hamilton Academical F.C.|Hamilton]]\n| 31 Dec 1953\n|-\n| {{flagicon|SCO}} [[Jim Davie]]\n| {{flagicon|ENG}} [[Shrewsbury Town F.C.|Shrewsbury]]\n| 23 Jan 1954\n|-\n| {{flagicon|SCO}} Willie Gibson\n| {{flagicon|SCO}} [[Forfar Athletic F.C.|Forfar Ath]]\n| 6 Feb 1954\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n\n==== Players out ====\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; font-size:95%;width:98%; text-align:left\"\n|-\n!Player\n!To\n!Date\n|-\n| {{flagicon|SCO}} [[Jimmy Scott (footballer, born 1927)|Jimmy Scott]]\n| {{flagicon|SCO}} [[Alloa Athletic F.C.|Alloa Ath]]\n| 29 Aug 1953\n|-\n| {{flagicon|SCO}} [[Jimmy Frame]]\n| {{flagicon|ENG}} [[Worcester City F.C.|Worcester City]]\n| 12 Sep 1953\n|-\n| {{flagicon|SCO}} Andy Tait\n| {{flagicon|SCO}} [[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]]\n| 26 Sep 1953\n|-\n| {{flagicon|SCO}} Jim Finnie\n| {{flagicon|SCO}} [[Ayr United F.C.|Ayr United]]\n| 26 Sep 1953\n|-\n| {{flagicon|SCO}} Tommy Martin\n| {{flagicon|SCO}} [[Forfar Athletic F.C.|Forfar Ath]]\n| 31 Oct 1953\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n<small>Source:<ref>{{cite book | last = Litster | first = John | title = Record of Post-War Scottish League Players | publisher = PM Publications | location = Norwich}}</ref></small>\n\n==Reserve team==\nDumbarton only played one official 'reserve' match in the Second XI Cup, losing in the first round to Third Lanark.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Dumbarton F.C. seasons}}\n{{1953\u201354 in Scottish football}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dumbarton}}\n[[Category:Dumbarton F.C. seasons]]\n[[Category:Scottish football clubs 1953\u201354 season]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2015}}\n{{Infobox football club season\n| club               = [[Dumbarton F.C.|Dumbarton]]\n| season             = 1953\u20131954\n| manager            = William Irvine\n| chairman           = \n| stadium            = Boghead Park, Dumbarton\n| league             = [[1953\u201354 Scottish Football League|Scottish League B Division]]\n| league result      = 16th\n| cup1               = [[1953\u201354 Scottish Cup|Scottish Cup]]\n| cup1 result        = First Round\n| cup2               = [[1953\u201354 Scottish League Cup|Scottish League Cup]]\n| cup2 result        = Prelims\n| league topscorer   = Jackie Malloch (13)\n| season topscorer   = Jackie Malloch (14)\n| highest attendance = \n| lowest attendance  = \n| average attendance = \n| pattern_la1        = _black_hoops\n| pattern_b1         = _goldhoops\n| pattern_ra1        = _black_hoops\n| pattern_so1        = _goldtop\n| leftarm1           = ffc100\n| body1              = 000000\n| rightarm1          = ffc100\n| shorts1            = ffffff\n| socks1             = 000000\n| prevseason         = [[1952\u201353 Dumbarton F.C. season|1952\u201353]]\n| nextseason         = [[1954\u201355 Dumbarton F.C. season|1954\u201355]]\n}}\n\nThe '''1953\u201354''' season was the 70th [[Football in Scotland|Scottish football]] season in which [[Dumbarton F.C.|Dumbarton]] competed at national level, entering the [[Scottish Football League]], the [[Scottish Cup]] and the [[Scottish League Cup]].  In addition Dumbarton competed in the [[Stirlingshire Cup]].\n\n==Scottish League==\n{{Main|1953\u201354 Scottish Football League}}\nAfter three seasons of mid-table finishes, Dumbarton fell to rock-bottom 16th place, with 22 points, 23 behind champions Motherwell.\n\nIn 1949, Division C merged with the Scottish Reserve League to form two regionalised divisions.  Only 'first XI's could be promoted from the newly formatted Division C, and this became an almost impossible task as the smaller teams had to face the 'second strings' of Division A.  It was however to be Dumbarton's fate that this season saw Brechin City win the North-East section of Division C, and so took Dumbarton's place in Division B. So for the first time since 1906, the club would play league football outside the top two divisions.\n\n{{football box collapsible\n|result  =L\n|date =5 September 1953\n|round =[[1953-54 Scottish Football League|Division B]]\n|score = 2-1<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fitbastats.com/dumbarton/game.php?gameid=11117 |title=Dundee United 2 - 1 Dumbarton, Scottish League (05/09/1953)|publisher=Fitbastats.com |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sonsarchive.com/matchdetails.php?id=1685 |title=Dundee United 2 - 1 Dumbarton, Saturday, September 5th 1953 |publisher=The Sons Archive |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n|team1 =[[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]]\n|team2 =[[Dumbarton F.C.|Dumbarton]]\n|goals1 =Cruickshanks {{goal|42}}<br>McKay {{goal|}}\n|goals2 =Malloch {{goal|}}\n|stadium =[[Tannadice Park]]\n|attendance =8,000\n|referee =H Phillips\n|motm =\n}}\n{{football box collapsible\n|result  =W\n|date =12 September 1953\n|round =[[1953-54 Scottish Football League|Division B]]\n|score = 5-1<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fitbastats.com/dumbarton/game.php?gameid=36734 |title=Dumbarton 5 - 1 Albion Rovers, Scottish League (12/09/1953)|publisher=Fitbastats.com |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sonsarchive.com/matchdetails.php?id=1686 |title=Dumbarton 5 - 1 Albion Rovers, Saturday, September 12th 1953 |publisher=The Sons Archive |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n|team1 =[[Dumbarton F.C.|Dumbarton]]\n|team2 =[[Albion Rovers F.C.|Albion Rovers]]\n|goals1 =Malloch {{goal|}}{{goal|}}<br>Donegan {{goal|44}}<br>McCaffrey {{goal|}}<br>McGairy {{goal|}}\n|goals2 =Docherty {{goal|}}\n|stadium =[[Boghead Park]]\n|attendance =\n|referee =D McKerracher\n|motm =\n}}\n{{football box collapsible\n|result  =L\n|date =19 September 1953\n|round =[[1953-54 Scottish Football League|Division B]]\n|score = 8-0<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fitbastats.com/dumbarton/game.php?gameid=36735 |title=Morton 8 - 0 Dumbarton, Scottish League (19/09/1953)|publisher=Fitbastats.com |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sonsarchive.com/matchdetails.php?id=1687 |title=Morton 8 - 0 Dumbarton, Saturday, September 19th 1953 |publisher=The Sons Archive |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n|team1 =[[Greenock Morton F.C.|Morton]]\n|team2 =[[Dumbarton F.C.|Dumbarton]]\n|goals1 =Hinshelwood {{goal|2}}<br>Gourlay {{goal|5}}{{goal|}}<br>Hannigan {{goal|16||69}}{{goal|}}<br>Linwood {{goal|}}{{goal|}}\n|goals2 =\n|stadium =[[Cappielow Park]]\n|attendance =\n|referee =D Murphy\n|motm =\n}}\n{{football box collapsible\n|result  =D\n|date =26 September 1953\n|round =[[1953-54 Scottish Football League|Division B]]\n|score = 4-4<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fitbastats.com/dumbarton/game.php?gameid=36736 |title=Dumbarton 4 - 4 Du